            <div type="commentary">
                <p><!--commented out pending revision-->
                    <!--to Marcus Valerius Chorton (son of Diognetos Megas), for his euergetism, by the Lilybaetanians, i.e. 'hoi Dekoriones M. Oualerion Diognetou Mega huion Chortana euergetan'; CIL 10.7240 is on the reverse of the stone - not a direct transl., but much the same thing viz. 'ordo et populus civit. Lilybit patrono perpetuo'. ordo et populus is transl. of boule kai demos; cf. IG 14.273 (also IG 14.575, from Centuripe). SEG 34.951 is another inscription containing the father of this man, which implies that this is not later than Augustan, since that is, so M-P, poss. C2 BC. SEG 37 is an observation simply that Megas is a name, not a tribal. Robert and Mason note that this inscription currently seems to be the unique example of the Greek transcr. of decurio in the sense of 'bouleutes'. cf. SEG.37.1814 andBE 1961.119--></p>
            </div>
